status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
GlobalMinVarPortfolios
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset space \space{}
\end_inset

we showed that the weight vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{w}_{mv}$
\end_inset

 that minimize portfolio variance, subject to the mean return and full investmen
t constraints 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{w}^{\prime}\bumu=\mu_{P}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{w}^{\prime}\mathbf{1}=1$
\end_inset

, has the form
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathbf{w}_{\mathrm{mv}}=\lambda_{1}\mathbf{C}^{-1}\bumu\,+\,\lambda_{2}\mathbf{C}^{-1}\boldsymbol{1}.\label{eq: minVarWtVectorGeneralForm}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Applying the mean return and full-investment constrains results in two equations
 in the two unknowns 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{2}$
\end_inset

, and the reader can easily show that the solution to these equations is
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{alignedat}{1}\lambda_{1} & =\dfrac{c\mu_{P}\,-\,a}{d}\\
\lambda_{2} & =\dfrac{b\,-\,a\mu_{P}}{d}
\end{alignedat}
\label{eq: theTwoLamdas}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $a=\mathbf{1}^{\prime}\mathbf{C}^{-1}\bumu$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $b=\bumu^{\prime}\mathbf{C}^{-1}\bumu$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $c=\mathbf{1}^{\prime}\mathbf{C}^{-1}\mathbf{1}>0$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $d=bc\,-\,a^{2}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Substituting 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{2}$
\end_inset

 into 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq: minVarWtVectorGeneralForm"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 and easy algebraic manipulation results in
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathbf{w}_{\mathrm{mv}}=\mathbf{w}_{1}\,+\,\mu_{P}\mathbf{w}_{2}\label{eq: minVarWtVector}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{alignedat}{1}\mathbf{w}_{1} & =\dfrac{1}{d}\left(b\mathbf{C}^{-1}\mathbf{1}\,-\,a\mathbf{C}^{-1}\bumu\right)\\
\mathbf{w}_{2} & =\dfrac{1}{d}\left(c\mathbf{C}^{-1}\bumu\,-\,a\mathbf{C}^{-1}\mathbf{1}\right).
\end{alignedat}
\label{eq: minVarPairOfWts}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
and
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
d & =(\bumu^{\mathrm{\prime}}\mathbf{C}^{-1}\bumu)({\bf 1^{\mathrm{\prime}}}\mathbf{C}^{-1}{\bf 1})\,-\,{\bf ({\bf 1^{\mathrm{\prime}}}}\mathbf{C}^{-1}\bumu)^{2}\label{eq: dExpression}\\
 & \geqslant0
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where we show below how the above inequality follows from the Cauchy-Schwarz
 inequality, and that 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 is positive except in the special case where 
\begin_inset Formula $\bum=c\mathbf{1}$
\end_inset

 for some constant 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

, which does not arise in practice.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Also, we note that
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{alignedat}{1}c^{-1} & =\sigma_{\mathrm{gmv}}^{2}\\
\dfrac{a}{c} & =\mu_{\mathrm{gmv}}
\end{alignedat}
\label{eq: constantsMore}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{\mathrm{gmv}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{\mathrm{gmv}}^{2}$
\end_inset

 are the mean and variance of the global minimum variance (GMV) portfolio.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Positivity of 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{d}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec: positivity of d"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{C}$
\end_inset

 is positive definite so is 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{C}^{-1}$
\end_inset

, and basic matrix theory shows that therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{C}^{-1}$
\end_inset

 can be factored into the product of two inverse square root matrices, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{C}^{-1}=\mathbf{C}^{-1/2}\mathbf{C}^{-1/2}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{C}^{-1/2}$
\end_inset

 is positive definite.
 Thus one has
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
d & =(\bumu^{\mathrm{\prime}}\mathbf{C}^{-1/2}\mathbf{C}^{-1/2}\bumu)\,\cdot\,({\bf 1^{\mathrm{\prime}}}\mathbf{C}^{-1/2}\mathbf{C}^{-1/2}{\bf 1})\,-\,{\bf ({\bf 1^{\mathrm{\prime}}}}\mathbf{C}^{-1/2}\mathbf{C}^{-1/2}{\bf \boldsymbol{\mu}})^{2}\\
 & =(\check{\bumu^{\prime}}\check{\bumu})\,\cdot\,(\check{\mathbf{1}}^{\mathrm{\prime}}\check{\mathbf{1}})\,-\,(\check{\mathbf{1}}^{\mathrm{\prime}}\check{{\bf \bumu}})^{2}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $\check{\bumu}=\mathbf{C}^{-1/2}\bumu$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\check{\mathbf{1}}=\mathbf{C}^{-1/2}{\bf 1}$
\end_inset

.
 The Cauchy-Schwarz inequality for two vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{y}$
\end_inset

 states that
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
{\bf ({\bf x^{\mathrm{\prime}}}}\mathbf{y})^{2}\leqslant{\bf ({\bf x^{\mathrm{\prime}}}}\mathbf{x})\,\cdot\,{\bf ({\bf y^{\mathrm{\prime}}}}\mathbf{y})\quad\mathrm{with\:equality\:if,\:and\:only\:if,}\quad\mathbf{y=\mathrm{\mathit{c\cdot\mathbf{x}}}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
for some non-zero constant 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 is equal to zero if and, only if, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{C}^{-1/2}\bumu=c\cdot\mathbf{C}^{-1/2}{\bf 1}$
\end_inset

, equivalently if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{C}^{-1/2}\left(\bumu\,-\,c\cdot\mathbf{1}\right)={\bf 0}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{0}$
\end_inset

 is a vector of zeros.
 But since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{C}^{-1/2}$
\end_inset


\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\xout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none
 is positive definite, the condition 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{C}^{-1/2}\left(\bumu\,-\,c\cdot\mathbf{1}\right)={\bf 0}$
\end_inset

 can only occur if 
\begin_inset Formula $\bumu=c\,\cdot\,\mathbf{1}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $d=0$
\end_inset

 if, and only if, the portfolio mean vector has all equal values, which
 essentially never happens in practice.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
The Tangent Portfolio is the Market Portfolio Under the CAPM
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec: tangentPortIsMktPortUnderCAPM"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Under the first CAPM assumption in 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
CAPM
\end_layout

\end_inset

, all market participants hold the tangent portfolio 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

, and the last assumption implies that the supply of securities equals the
 demand.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 be the number of securities in the market, with 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{j}$
\end_inset

 be the market capitalization of the 
\begin_inset Formula $j^{th}$
\end_inset

 security.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $V=\sum_{j\,=\,1}^{N}V_{j}$
\end_inset

 is the total market capitalization, and 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{M,\,j}=V_{j}/V$
\end_inset

 is the weight of the 
\begin_inset Formula $j^{th}$
\end_inset

 security in the market portfolio.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 be the number of market investors, where the 
\begin_inset Formula $k^{th}$
\end_inset

 investor invests an amount 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{k}W_{k},\ 0<\gamma_{k}<1$
\end_inset

 in risky assets and an amount 
\begin_inset Formula $W_{k}(1-\gamma_{k})$
\end_inset

 in the risk-free asset.
 In general the 
\begin_inset Formula $k^{th}$
\end_inset

 investor would invest an amount 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{k}W_{k}w_{k,\,j}$
\end_inset

 in the 
\begin_inset Formula $j^{th}$
\end_inset

 market asset, and therefore the total amount invested in the 
\begin_inset Formula $j^{th}$
\end_inset

 asset by all investors is
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\dot{V}_{j}=\sum_{k\,=\,1}^{K}\gamma_{k}\,W_{k}\,w_{k,\,j}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
However, under the CAPM assumptions all investors all hold the same tangent
 portfolio, so 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{k,\,j}=w_{j},\,k=1,\,2\,,\cdots,\,K$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{j}$
\end_inset

 is the weight of the 
\begin_inset Formula $j^{th}$
\end_inset

 asset in the tangent portfolio 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{j\,=\,1}^{N}w_{j}=1$
\end_inset

.
 Thus
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\dot{V}_{j}=w_{j}\sum_{k\,=\,1}^{K}\gamma_{k}\,W_{k}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
is the amount invested by all investors in the 
\begin_inset Formula $j^{th}$
\end_inset

 asset, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{V}=\sum_{j\,=\,1}^{N}\dot{V}_{j}=\sum_{k\,=\,1}^{K}\gamma_{k}\,W_{k}$
\end_inset

 is the total amount invested by all investors.
 However, under the CAPM equilibrium assumption 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{V}_{j}=V_{j}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{V}=V$
\end_inset

, which results in
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
w_{M,\,j}=\dfrac{V_{j}}{V}=\dfrac{\dot{V}_{j}}{\dot{V}}=w_{j},\ j=1,\,2,\,\cdots\,,\,N
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
and so the tangent portfolio 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 is the market portfolio 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
\noindent

\series bold
Proof of the CAPM
\series default

\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec: CAPMproof"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The following is a simple proof of the CAPM formula 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
CAPMformula
\end_layout

\end_inset

 with beta defined by 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
CAPMbeta
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 be the market portfolio whose mean return and variance are 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{M}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{M}^{2}$
\end_inset

 respectively.
 As the market portfolio is the tangent portfolio, the Capital Allocation
 Line associated with the entire market is known as the 
\emph on
Capital Market Line
\emph default
 (CML), and can be written as 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mu=r_{f}\,+\,\dfrac{(\mu_{M}\,-\,r_{f})}{\sigma_{M}}\sigma.\label{eq: CML}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now consider any security in the market place with return 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{i}$
\end_inset

, mean 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{i}$
\end_inset

 and variance 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{i}^{2}$
\end_inset

, such that 
\begin_inset Formula $(\mu_{i},\sigma_{i})$
\end_inset

 does not lie on the efficient frontier.
 We form a portfolio 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 by investing a fraction 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 in the security and a fraction 
\begin_inset Formula $1-\alpha$
\end_inset

, in the market portfolio 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
 The mean return and variance of the portfolio 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 are:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mu_{P} & =\alpha\mu_{i}\,+\,(1\,-\,\alpha)\mu_{M}\\
\sigma_{P} & =\left(\alpha^{2}\sigma_{i}^{2}\,+\,2\,\alpha\,(1\,-\,\alpha)\,\sigma_{i,\,M}\,+\,(1\,-\,\alpha)^{2}\sigma_{M}^{2}\right)^{1/2}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The pair 
\begin_inset Formula $(\mu_{P},\,\sigma_{P})=(\mu_{P}(\alpha),\,\sigma_{P}(\alpha))$
\end_inset

 traces out a 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{P}(\alpha)$
\end_inset

 versus 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{P}(\alpha)$
\end_inset

 curve in portfolio mean return versus standard deviation space as 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 varies from 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

, with value 
\begin_inset Formula $(\mu_{i},\,\sigma_{i})$
\end_inset

 when 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=1$
\end_inset

 and value 
\begin_inset Formula $(\mu_{M},\,\sigma_{M})$
\end_inset

 when 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=0$
\end_inset

.
 This curve can never lie above or to the left of the CML (if it did, the
 CML would not be optimal), and the slope of the curve at 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=0$
\end_inset

 is
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\dfrac{d\mu}{d\sigma}(\alpha)\Biggr|_{\alpha=0} & =\dfrac{d\mu/d\alpha\bigr|_{\alpha=0}}{d\sigma/d\alpha\bigr|_{\alpha=0}},\label{eq: DmuDsigmaFunction}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where the derivative of the numerator is equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{i}\,-\,\mu_{M}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 including 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=0$
\end_inset

.
 Straightforward calculus yields an expression for 
\begin_inset Formula $d\sigma/d\alpha$
\end_inset

 that reduces to 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\sigma_{i,\,M}\,-\,\sigma_{M}^{2}\right)/\sigma_{M}$
\end_inset

 when 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=0$
\end_inset

.
 Thus
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\dfrac{d\mu}{d\sigma}(\alpha)\Biggr|_{\alpha=0}=\sigma_{M}\dfrac{\mu_{i}\,-\,\mu_{M}}{\sigma_{i,\,M}\,-\,\sigma_{M}^{2}}\label{eq: DmuDsigmaAtMarketPort}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A small but important step in the proof is a straightforward verification
 that the derivative function 
\begin_inset Formula $\dfrac{d\mu}{d\sigma}(\alpha)$
\end_inset

 is continuous at 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=0$
\end_inset

.
 Thus at 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=0$
\end_inset

 the derivative 
\begin_inset Formula $\dfrac{d\mu}{d\sigma}(\alpha)$
\end_inset

 is tangent to the CML, and so its slope must equal that of the CML, or
 
\begin_inset Formula $(\mu_{M}-r_{f})/\sigma_{M})$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The reason is that if the curve of portfolio 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 is not tangent to the CML, its variance would be lower than the CML variance
 for 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{P}$
\end_inset

 in some neighborhood of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{M}$
\end_inset

, contradicting the optimality of the CML.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 It follows that
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mu_{M}\,-\,r_{f}=\sigma_{M}^{2}\,\dfrac{\mu_{i}\,-\,\mu_{M}}{\sigma_{i,\,M}\,-\,\sigma_{M}^{2}},\label{eq: CAPMderivation}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
which, upon rearrangement, yields the CAPM.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
An alternative proof of the CAPM using the mathematics of Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec: mvoCashAndRiskyAssets"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 is left as an 
\series bold
Exercise
\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\series bold
Alternate Proof of the CAPM
\series default

\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec: alternateCAPMProof"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Under the assumptions stated in Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec: CAPM"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, the tangent portfolio T is the market portfolio M and the tangent portfolio
 weight vector 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:TanPortWts"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 is market portfolio weights vector is
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
{\bf w}_{M}=\frac{\mathbf{C}^{-1}{\bf \boldsymbol{\mu}}_{e}}{\mathbf{1^{\prime}}\mathbf{C}^{-1}{\bf \boldsymbol{\mu}}_{e}}
\]

\end_inset

which can be re–arranged to give
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{{\bf \boldsymbol{\mu}}_{e}}\boldsymbol{=}\left(\mathbf{1^{\prime}}\mathbf{C}^{-1}{\bf \boldsymbol{\mu}}_{e}\right)\cdot\mathbf{C}{\bf w}_{M}.
\]

\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\mathbf{C}{\bf w}_{M}\right)_{i}=cov(r_{i},r_{M}),\,i=1,\cdots,N$
\end_inset

, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mu_{e,i} & =\mu_{i}-r_{f}\\
 & =\left(\mathbf{1^{\prime}}\mathbf{C}^{-1}{\bf \boldsymbol{\mu}}_{e}\right)\cdot cov(r_{i},r_{M}).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

The market excess return is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mu_{M,e}=\mu_{M}-r_{f}=\bum_{e}^{\prime}\mathbf{w}_{M}=\frac{\bum_{e}^{\prime}\mathbf{C}^{-1}{\bf \boldsymbol{\mu}}_{e}}{\mathbf{1^{\prime}}\mathbf{C}^{-1}{\bf \boldsymbol{\mu}}_{e}}
\]

\end_inset

and the market variance is
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\sigma_{M}^{2} & =\frac{\bum_{e}^{\prime}\mathbf{C}^{-1}\mathbf{C}\mathbf{C}^{-1}{\bf \boldsymbol{\mu}}_{e}}{\left(\mathbf{1^{\prime}}\mathbf{C}^{-1}{\bf \boldsymbol{\mu}}_{e}\right)^{2}}\\
 & =\frac{\bum_{e}^{\prime}\mathbf{C}^{-1}{\bf \boldsymbol{\mu}}_{e}}{\left(\mathbf{1^{\prime}}\mathbf{C}^{-1}{\bf \boldsymbol{\mu}}_{e}\right)^{2}}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Thus
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbf{1^{\prime}}\mathbf{C}^{-1}{\bf \boldsymbol{\mu}}_{e}=\frac{\mu_{M,e}}{\sigma_{M}^{2}}
\]

\end_inset

 and so we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mu_{i}-r_{f}=\left(\mu_{M}-r_{f}\right)\cdot\frac{cov(r_{i},r_{M})}{\sigma_{M}^{2}},\,i=1,\cdots,N.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\series bold
CAPM Time Series Model Inconsistency
\series default

\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec: timeSeriesCAPMinconsistency"

\end_inset

 
\series bold
Move this to Chapter 4.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
It is sometimes assumed by practitioners that equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq: tseriesCAPM"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{i}=0$
\end_inset

 is equivalent to the CAPM given by 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq: CAPM"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 But this is not exactly true, as there is an inconsistency between the
 two equations that can be seen as follows.
 If we substitute 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq: tseriesCAPM"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{i}=0$
\end_inset

 into the representation of market return as a value weighted sum of asset
 returns, and recall that the market beta 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{M}=\sum_{i=1}^{N}w_{M,i}\beta_{i}$
\end_inset

 is equal to one, we get
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
r_{M,t} & =\sum_{i=1}^{N}w_{M,i}r_{i,t}\\
 & =\sum_{i=1}^{N}w_{M,i}\cdot(\beta_{i}\cdot r_{M,t}+\varepsilon_{i,t})\\
 & =r_{M,t}+\sum_{i=1}^{N}w_{M,i}\varepsilon_{i,t}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
which implies that the summation term on the right-hand side of the last
 line above is zero.
 Although this summation is typically quite small for large 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

, it is rarely if ever exactly equal to zero.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Zero Beta CAPM Derivation
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec: zeroBetaCAPMderivation"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here we provide a simple derivation of the Zero Beta CAPM using MinVar portfolio
 results in Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec: minVarMath"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 The assumptions we use are the same as those for the standard CAPM, except
 for the assumption that there is no risk–free asset available.
 A further difference from the standard CAPM setup is that different investors
 will take different positions on the efficient frontier.
 However, in equilibrium, the market portfolio 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is a convex combination of efficient portfolios of all investors, and is
 therefore efficient.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Recall from equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq: minVarWtVectorGeneralForm"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 that the weight vector of a MinVar efficient portfolio 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

, with return 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{p}$
\end_inset

 and mean return 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{p}$
\end_inset

, has the form
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbf{w}_{p}=\lambda\mathbf{C}^{-1}\bumu\,+\,\gamma\mathbf{C}^{-1}\mathbf{1}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It follows that for any other portfolio 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 with weight vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{w}_{q}$
\end_inset

, return 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{q}$
\end_inset

 and mean return 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{q}$
\end_inset

, the covariance of 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{p}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{q}$
\end_inset

 is
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\mathrm{cov}(r_{p},\,r_{q}) & =\mathbf{w}_{q}^{\prime}\mathbf{C}\mathbf{w}_{p}\nonumber \\
 & =\lambda\mathbf{w}_{q}^{\prime}\bumu\,+\,\gamma\mathbf{w}_{q}^{\prime}\mathbf{1}\nonumber \\
 & =\lambda\mu_{q}\,+\,\gamma.\label{eq: cov(r_p,r_q)-initial}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A portfolio that is constrained to have zero covariance with respect to
 an efficient frontier portfolio 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is called a 
\emph on
zero covariance portfolio
\emph default
.
 A fully-invested zero-covariance portfolio 
\begin_inset Formula $zc(p)$
\end_inset

, that has weight vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{w}_{zc(p)}$
\end_inset

, return 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{zc(p)}$
\end_inset

, and mean return 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{zc(p)}$
\end_inset

, satisfies
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\mathrm{cov}(r_{p},\,r_{zc(p)}) & =\lambda\mathbf{w}_{zc(p)}^{\prime}\bumu\,+\,\gamma\mathbf{w}_{zc(p)}^{\prime}\mathbf{1}\nonumber \\
 & =\lambda\mu_{zc(p)}\,+\,\gamma\nonumber \\
 & =0.\label{eq: cov(r_p,r_zc(p))}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A formula for a zero beta portfolio weight vector is derived in TS 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec: zeroCovariancePortfolios"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, where the frontier geometray of zero Beta portfolios is discussed.
 Solving for 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq: cov(r_p,r_zc(p))"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 and substituting in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq: cov(r_p,r_q)-initial"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 gives
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\mathrm{cov}(r_{p},\,r_{q}) & =\lambda(\mu_{q}\,-\,\mu_{zc(p)})\label{eq: cov(r_p,r_q)}\\
\mathrm{var}(r_{p}) & =\lambda(\mu_{p}\,-\,\mu_{zc(p)}).\label{eq: var(r_p)}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Dividing 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq: cov(r_p,r_q)"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq: var(r_p)"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, rearranging and let 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 be the market portfolio 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

, we have: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mu_{q}=\mu_{zc(M)}\,+\,\beta_{q,\,M}(\mu_{M}\,-\,\mu_{zc(M)}).\label{eq: zeroBetaCAPMportLevel}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since the portfolio 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 is an arbitrary fully-invested portfolio, it can be an individual asset
 with index 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 , which results in the asset level zero-beta CAPM:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mu_{j}=\mu_{zc(M)}\,+\,\beta_{j,\,M}\,(\mu_{M}\,-\,\mu_{zc(M)}).\label{eq: zeroBetaCAPM}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Zero Covariance Frontier Portfolios
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec: zeroCovariancePortfolios"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Any portfolio 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 that has zero covariance with respect to another portfolio 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 is a portfolio whose beta with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 is zero, i.e., 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{pq}=0$
\end_inset

, and the portfolio 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is called a 
\emph on
zero beta
\emph default
 portfolio.
 It turns out that a portfolio or asset that has a zero beta with respect
 to the market portfolio is the basis of a 
\emph on
zero beta CAPM
\emph default
, which we discussed in the previous Section.
 Here we discuss the special case of zero covariance frontier portfolios.
 It turns out the zero covariance frontier portfolios are inefficient, and
 since the MaxQU approach only gives efficient frontier portfolios, we use
 instead the MinVar optimization results.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 denote any efficient frontier portfolio not equal to the global minimum
 variance portfolio, and define 
\begin_inset Formula $zc(p)$
\end_inset

 to be a frontier portfolio that has a zero covariance with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 The expected value of the 
\begin_inset Formula $zc(p)$
\end_inset

 portfolio is easily found from general expression 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
covTwoFrontierPortfolios
\end_layout

\end_inset

 for the covariance between any two frontier portfolios, which in this case
 is
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{alignedat}{1}\mathrm{cov}(r_{zc(p)},\,r_{p}) & =\sigma_{\mathrm{gmv}}^{2}\,+\,\dfrac{c}{d}\left(\mu_{zc(p)}\,-\,\mu_{\mathrm{gmv}}\right)\left(\mu_{p}\,-\,\mu_{\mathrm{gmv}}\right)\\
 & =0
\end{alignedat}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $c=\mathbf{1}^{\prime}\mathbf{C}^{-1}\mathbf{1}>0$
\end_inset

 and the formula for the positive constant 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 is given by 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq: dExpression"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 It follows that the expected return of the zero covariance frontier portfolio
 is given by the formula: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mu_{zc(p)}=\mu_{\mathrm{gmv}}\,-\,\dfrac{d}{c}\,\cdot\,\dfrac{\sigma_{\mathrm{gmv}}^{2}}{\mu_{p}\,-\,\mu_{\mathrm{gmv}}}.\label{eq: zeroBetaPortMean}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is any efficient frontier portfolio other than the GMV portfolio it follows
 that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{p}>\mu_{\mathrm{gmv}}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus the second term above is positive and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{zc(p)}<\mu_{\mathrm{gmv}}$
\end_inset

, i.e., the mean return of the zero covariance frontier portfolio is always
 less than that of the GMV portfolio.
 This means that the zero covariance portfolio is an inefficient frontier
 portfolio, i.e., it lies on the lower half of the portfolio frontier that
 corresponds to the minus sign in 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
minVarFrontierRisky
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 The zero covariance portfolio weight vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{w}_{zc(p)}$
\end_inset

 corresponding to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{zc(p)}$
\end_inset

 is uniquely defined by 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq: minVarWtVector"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 as:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathbf{w}_{zc(p)}=\mathbf{w}_{1}\,+\,\mu_{zc(p)}\mathbf{w}_{2}.\label{eq: zeroBetaPortWeight}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It turns out that the relationship between the efficient frontier portfolio
 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

, the GMV portfolio 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{gmv}$
\end_inset

 and the zero covariance portfolio 
\begin_inset Formula $zc(p)$
\end_inset

 is described by the straight line in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig: zero-covariancePortfolioGeometry"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 Note in particular that the straight line connecting portfolios 
\begin_inset Formula $zc(p)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 goes through the portfolio 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{gmv}$
\end_inset

.
 NOTE: In the figure the 
\emph on
gmv
\emph default
 is referred to as the MVP.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
I borrowed the Figure below from Huang and Litzenberger, and will eventually
 replace it with an original.
 Doug
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\noindent
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename Plots/zeroBetaPort graph.PNG
	lyxscale 30
	scale 60

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Relationship between portfolios 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{gmv}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $zc(p)$
\end_inset

 in mean return versus variance coordinates.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig: zero-covariancePortfolioGeometry"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It can be shown that the straight line in the above figure is given by
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mu_{r}=\mu_{zc(p)}\,+\,\dfrac{\mu_{p}\,-\,\mu_{gmv}}{\sigma_{p}^{2}\,-\,\sigma_{gmv}^{2}}\,\sigma_{r}^{2}\label{eq: zc(p) geometry}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
and that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{r}=\mu_{gmv}$
\end_inset

 when 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{r}^{2}=\sigma_{gmv}^{2}$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\series bold
Old Approach in HL, not used here
\series default
.
 The above result is obtained rather easily because of the restriction that
 the zero-beta portfolio 
\begin_inset Formula $Pz$
\end_inset

 must be a frontier portfolio.
 It turns out that for the zero-beta CAPM, a more general result is required
 where 
\begin_inset Formula $Pz$
\end_inset

 can be any achievable fully invested portfolio.
 This result is a bit more involved, so we sketch the development here,
 leaving it as Exercise to fill in some of the details.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Old and Not Used.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $Pe$
\end_inset

 be an efficient frontier portfolio, other than the GMV portfolio, with
 returns 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{Pe}$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 be any other fully-invested portfolio with returns 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{P}$
\end_inset

.
 The covariance between 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{Pe}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{P}$
\end_inset

 is
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathrm{cov}(r_{Pe},r_{P}) & =\mathbf{w}_{Pe}^{\prime}\mathbf{C}\mathbf{w}_{P}\\
 & =\lambda_{1}\bumu^{\prime}\mathbf{C}^{-1}\mathbf{C}\mathbf{w}_{P}+\lambda_{2}\mathbf{1}^{\prime}\mathbf{C}^{-1}\mathbf{C}\mathbf{w}_{P}\\
 & =\lambda_{1}\mu_{P}+\lambda_{2}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
where the second equality follows from 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq: minvarWtvecGeneral"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 Now substituting the values of the two Lagrange multipliers from
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq: theTwoLamdas"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, and solving for 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{Pe}$
\end_inset

 gives
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mu_{P}=\dfrac{a\mu_{Pe}-b}{c\mu_{Pe}-a}+\mathrm{cov}(r_{Pe},r_{P})\dfrac{d}{c(\mu_{Pe}-\mu_{gmv})}.\label{eq: zeroBetaPortFirstStep}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Somewhat remarkably, the first term above can be shown (as an 
\series bold
Exercise
\series default
) to have the form
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mu_{\mathrm{gmv}}-\dfrac{d}{c}\cdot\dfrac{\sigma_{\mathrm{gmv}}^{2}}{\mu_{Pe}-\mu_{\mathrm{gmv}}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
given by the right-hand side of the zero-beta portfolio mean return expression
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq: zeroBetaPortMean"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 replaced by 
\begin_inset Formula $Pe$
\end_inset

.
 Thus the above expression is equal to the mean 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{Pez}$
\end_inset

 of the 
\begin_inset Formula $Pe$
\end_inset

 zero-beta portfolio 
\begin_inset Formula $Pez$
\end_inset

.
 With some additional effort, using the expression 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq: minvarPortVariance"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, one can show (another 
\series bold
Exercise
\series default
) that the second term above is equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{P,Pe}(\mu_{Pe}-\mu_{Pez})$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{P,Pe}=\mathrm{cov}(r_{P},r_{Pe})/\mathrm{var}(r_{Pe})$
\end_inset

.
 Thus we have the following portfolio 
\begin_inset Formula $Pe$
\end_inset

 zero-beta portfolio 
\begin_inset Formula $Pez$
\end_inset

 representation of the expected value of portfolio 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\mu_{Pez} & =\mu_{Pez}+\beta_{P,Pe}(\mu_{Pe}-\mu_{Pez})\\
 & =(1-\beta_{P,Pe})\mu_{Pez}+\beta_{P,Pe}\mu_{Pe}.
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
We don't need the following material here, maybe use it later if we find
 a valuable application of it, e.g., robust regression, penalized regression
 such as Lasso, Elastic Net.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\series bold
Portfolio Optimization via Linear Regression
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Consider the returns data based MinVar problem
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\min\limits _{{\bf w}}\sigma_{P}^{2}({\bf w)}=\min\limits _{{\bf w}}{\bf w'}\boldsymbol{\hat{\Sigma}}{\bf w},\qquad\mathbf{w\,\epsilon\,C}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\noindent
where 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\hat{\Sigma}}$
\end_inset

 is an estimate of the unkown returns covariance matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\Sigma}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{\boldsymbol{W}}$
\end_inset

 is the set of all 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{w}$
\end_inset

 that satisfy a set of linear inequality constraints.
 The classical estimator of 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\Sigma}$
\end_inset

 is the sample covariance matrix
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\boldsymbol{\hat{\Sigma}}=\dfrac{1}{T}\sum_{t=1}^{T}(\mathbf{r}_{t}-\boldsymbol{\hat{\mu}})(\mathbf{r}_{t}-\boldsymbol{\hat{\mu}})',\qquad\qquad\hat{\Sigma}_{ij}=\dfrac{1}{T}\sum_{t=1}^{T}(r_{it}-\hat{\mu}_{i})(r_{jt}-\hat{\mu}_{j}),\quad i,j=1,\cdots,n\label{eq:sampleCov-1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\noindent
where
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\boldsymbol{\hat{\mu}}=\dfrac{1}{T}\sum_{t=1}^{T}\mathbf{r}_{t},\qquad\qquad\hat{\mu}=\dfrac{1}{T}\sum_{t=1}^{T}r_{it},\quad i=1,\cdots,n.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\noindent
This allows us to write
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
T\cdot{\bf w'}\boldsymbol{\hat{\Sigma}}{\bf w} & =\sum_{t=1}^{T}{\bf w'}(\mathbf{r}_{t}-\boldsymbol{\hat{\mu}})(\mathbf{r}_{t}-\boldsymbol{\hat{\mu}})'{\bf w}\\
 & =\sum_{t=1}^{T}\left({\bf w'}(\mathbf{r}_{t}-\boldsymbol{\hat{\mu}})\right)^{2}\\
 & =\sum_{t=1}^{T}({\bf w'}\mathbf{r}_{t}-\hat{r}_{P}(\mathbf{w}))^{2},\qquad\hat{r}_{P}(\mathbf{w})={\bf w'\boldsymbol{\hat{\mu}}}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\noindent
and minimization of sum of squares on the right-hand side subject to constraints
 is equivalent to solveing the MinVar problem.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Consider the minimization problem
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\underset{\gamma,\mathbf{w}}{min}\sum_{t=1}^{T}({\bf w'}\mathbf{r}_{t}+\gamma)^{2}\label{eq:minVarasReg-1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\noindent
and minimize first with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

.
 Setting the derivative with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 equal to zero gives
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
-2\cdot\sum_{t=1}^{T}({\bf w'}\mathbf{r}_{t}+\gamma)=0
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
whose solution for 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\gamma & =-\frac{1}{T}\sum_{t=1}^{T}{\bf w'}\mathbf{r}_{t}\\
 & =-{\bf w'}\frac{1}{T}\sum_{t=1}^{T}\mathbf{r}_{t}\\
 & =-\mathbf{w}'\boldsymbol{\hat{\mu}}\\
 & =-\hat{r}_{P}(\mathbf{w}).
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Now consider the linear regression model
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
y_{t}=\gamma+\mathbf{r}_{t}'\mathbf{w}+\varepsilon_{t},\quad,t=1,\cdots,T.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The least-squares estimates of the unknown coefficient 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{w}$
\end_inset

 are the solution of the minimization problem
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\underset{\gamma,\mathbf{w}}{min}\sum_{t=1}^{T}({\bf \mathit{y_{t}}-\gamma-w'}\mathbf{r}_{t})^{2}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
which reveals that the MinVar minimization (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:minVarasReg-1"

\end_inset

) is equivalent to solving the above least squares regression problem in
 which one sets 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{t}=0,$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\:t=1,\cdots,T$
\end_inset

.
 However, keep in mind that the minimization is to be done under the constraint
 that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{w}\,\epsilon\,\mathcal{\boldsymbol{W}}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Once one realizes how the constrained MinVar problem can be treated as a
 special least-squares regression problem, it suggests that in addition
 to using least-squares to solve the problem, one can use orther regression
 fitting methods than least square.
 For example one can use robust regression in which the quadratic loss function
 is replaced by some robustifying loss function (see for example Maronna,
 Martin and Yohai, 2006).
 Or one can use modern penalized regression methods that result in parsimonious
 models that have a relatively small number of coefficients among a possible
 large number of coefficients, e.g., least-angle regression (LAR) and the
 Lasso method.
 See for example Hastie, Tibshirani and Friedman (2009).
 In the present context such regression methods would result in a relatively
 small number of non-zero portfolio weights among a possible 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 non-zero weights.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Proof of the APT
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec: APTproof"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a}=(a_{1},\,a_{2},\,\cdots\,,\,a_{n})^{\prime}$
\end_inset

 of intercepts in 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
APTintercepts
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset space \space{}
\end_inset

 may be written in the least-squares regression fit-plus-residuals form
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{alignedat}{1}\mathbf{a} & =\hat{\lambda}_{0}\mathbf{1}\,+\,\text{\mathbf{B}\ensuremath{\hat{\boldsymbol{\lambda}}}}\,+\,\ensuremath{\mathbf{u}}\end{alignedat}
\label{eq: LSregression-avec-on-Bmat}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\lambda}_{0}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\boldsymbol{\lambda}}=(\hat{\lambda}_{1},\,\hat{\lambda}_{2},\,\cdots\,,\,\hat{\lambda}_{K})^{\prime}$
\end_inset

 are the least-squares regression coefficients, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\ensuremath{\mathbf{u}}=(u_{1},\,u_{2},\,\cdots\,,\,u_{n})^{\prime}$
\end_inset

 is the vector of regression residuals.
 For details on the above LS regression decomposition see 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
LeastSquaresSection
\end_layout

\end_inset

, where it is shown that the regression residuals vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\ensuremath{\mathbf{u}}$
\end_inset

 is orthogonal to the vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{1}$
\end_inset

 as well as to the columns of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{B}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}^{\prime}\mathbf{1}=\sum_{i\,=\,1}^{n}u_{i}=0$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}^{\prime}\mathbf{B}=\mathbf{0}^{\prime}$
\end_inset

 where the right hand side is a vector of 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 zeros.
 It follows of course that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

 is orthogonal to the fit 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a}=\hat{\lambda}_{0}\mathbf{1}+\text{\mathbf{B}\ensuremath{\hat{\boldsymbol{\lambda}}}}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider the zero investment portfolio weights vector
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathbf{w=}\frac{\ensuremath{\mathbf{u}}}{\sqrt{n}\mathrm{\left\Vert \ensuremath{\mathbf{u}}\right\Vert }}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\Vert \ensuremath{\mathbf{u}}\right\Vert =\sqrt{\sum_{i\,=\,1}^{n}u_{i}^{2}}$
\end_inset

.
 Then using 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
APTreturnsModel
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset space \space{}
\end_inset

 along with the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}^{\prime}\mathbf{B}=\mathbf{0}^{\prime}$
\end_inset

, the arbitrage portfolio 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 has return
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
r_{p} & =\mathbf{w}^{\prime}\mathbf{r}\nonumber \\
 & =\dfrac{1}{\sqrt{n}\left\Vert \ensuremath{\mathbf{u}}\right\Vert }(\mathbf{u}^{\prime}\mathbf{a}\,+\,\mathbf{u}^{\prime}\bueps)\label{eq: arbPortfolioReturn}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
and since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{E}(\bueps)=0$
\end_inset

, the arbitrage portfolio has mean
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\mu_{p} & =\dfrac{\mathbf{u}^{\prime}\mathbf{a}}{\sqrt{n}\left\Vert \ensuremath{\mathbf{u}}\right\Vert }\nonumber \\
 & =\dfrac{\mathbf{u}^{\prime}\ensuremath{\mathbf{u}}}{\sqrt{n}\left\Vert \ensuremath{\mathbf{u}}\right\Vert }\nonumber \\
 & =\dfrac{1}{\sqrt{n}}\left\Vert \ensuremath{\mathbf{u}}\right\Vert \label{eq: arbPorMean}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where the second line is due to substituting 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq: LSregression-avec-on-Bmat"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a}$
\end_inset

 and using the orthogonality of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{B}$
\end_inset

, and the last line is because 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}^{\prime}\ensuremath{\mathbf{u}}=\left\Vert \ensuremath{\mathbf{u}}\right\Vert ^{2}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The variance of the arbitrage portfolio 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{p}$
\end_inset

 is
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\mathrm{E}(r_{p}-\mu_{p})^{2} & =\mathrm{E}\left(\dfrac{\mathbf{u}^{\prime}\bueps}{\sqrt{n}\left\Vert \ensuremath{\mathbf{u}}\right\Vert }\right)^{2}\nonumber \\
 & =\dfrac{\mathbf{u}^{\prime}\mathbf{C}\mathbf{u}}{n\left\Vert \ensuremath{\mathbf{u}}\right\Vert ^{2}}\label{eq: arbPortRisk}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{C}$
\end_inset

 is the covariance matrix of the errors 
\begin_inset Formula $\bueps=(\epsilon_{1},\,\epsilon_{2},\,\cdots,\,\epsilon_{n})^{\prime}$
\end_inset

.
 We say that the arbitrage portfolio is 
\emph on
asymptotically risk diversifiable 
\emph default
(ARD) if
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\underset{n\rightarrow\infty}{\lim}\dfrac{\mathbf{u}^{\prime}\mathbf{C}\mathbf{u}}{n\left\Vert \ensuremath{\mathbf{u}}\right\Vert ^{2}}=0.\label{eq: asympRiskDiversifiable}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The simplest condition that results in ARD is where the 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon_{i}$
\end_inset

 are uncorrelated and have bounded variances 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{i}^{2}<B$
\end_inset

, for in that case 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}^{\prime}\mathbf{C}\mathbf{u}=\sum_{i\,=\,1}^{n}u_{i}^{2}\sigma_{i}^{2}<B\sum_{i\,=\,1}^{n}u_{i}^{2}$
\end_inset

 and the above ratio is bounded by 
\begin_inset Formula $B/n$
\end_inset

, which goes to 0 as 
\begin_inset Formula $n\rightarrow\infty$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
I will add a little discussion down below on the practical implications
 of the ARD, and also, that the APT suggests why it is ok to use a single
 intercept parameter in 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

good
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 fundamental factor models.
 Doug
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose the portfolio is ARD and that 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mu_{p,\,\infty} & =\underset{n\rightarrow\infty}{\lim}\dfrac{1}{\sqrt{n}}\left\Vert \ensuremath{\mathbf{u}}\right\Vert \\
 & =\underset{n\rightarrow\infty}{\lim}\left(\dfrac{1}{n}\sum_{i\,=\,1}^{n}u_{i}^{2}\right)\\
 & >0.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In that case, the arbitrage portfolio has an asymptotic sure profit with
 no risk.
 But in a market that is arbitrage free this is not possible, and it must
 be that the APT condition
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
lim_{n\rightarrow\infty}\left(\dfrac{1}{n}\sum_{i\,=\,1}^{n}u_{i}^{2}\right)=0
\]

\end_inset

is satisfied.
\end_layout

